<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,602,222,282]" box="[151,602,222,248]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,602,222,248]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="de Winton, 1902" authorityName="de Winton" authorityYear="1902" box="[151,602,222,248]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,602,222,248]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,391,222,248]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Gerbillus andersoni</emphasis>
de Winton, 1902
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,602,222,282]" box="[151,557,257,282]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,343,257,282]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Common name:</emphasis>
Anderson’s gerbil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,329,714]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,329,354]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This is a medium sized gerbil closely resembling other hairy-footed gerbils. Hair on the back is yellowish with gray buff, darker than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="gerbillus (Olivier" authorityYear="1801" box="[585,718,365,390]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gerbillus">
<emphasis box="[585,718,365,390]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. gerbillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Tail is densely covered with hair throughout, terminating in a small tuft, terminal pencil intermediate in size between the well-developed of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="gerbillus (Olivier" authorityYear="1801" box="[1030,1161,401,426]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gerbillus">
<emphasis box="[1030,1161,401,426]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. gerbillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the scanty tuft in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Under parts are pure white with a distinct line of demarcation (
<figureCitation box="[985,1098,437,462]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1593,1615]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,766,1571]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,766,1571]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 35. Anderson’s gerbil, Gerbillus andersoni (photo by Mohammad Abu Baker)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202847/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figure 35</figureCitation>
). The dark pigmentation of its ears distinguishes this species from the other hairy-footed gerbil found in Jordan. Head and body length measures between 
<quantity box="[254,377,510,534]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.9" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.8" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="89.0" valueMax="90.0" valueMin="88.0">88–90 mm</quantity>
and tail length between 
<quantity box="[662,817,509,534]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" metricValueMax="1.28" metricValueMin="1.26" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="127.0" valueMax="128.0" valueMin="126.0">126–128 mm</quantity>
. It is slightly larger than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="gerbillus (Olivier" authorityYear="1801" box="[1108,1241,509,534]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gerbillus">
<emphasis box="[1108,1241,509,534]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. gerbillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. White spots are found above eyes and behind ears. Skull of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Winton" authorityYear="1902" box="[644,787,545,570]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis box="[644,787,545,570]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. andersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly larger than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="gerbillus (Olivier" authorityYear="1801" box="[1120,1251,545,570]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gerbillus">
<emphasis box="[1120,1251,545,570]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. gerbillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Greatest length of the skull may reach up to 29.0 mm. Tympanic bulla not developed. Posterior margin of the nasal bone is truncate. Incisive foramina long, exceeding tooth row length, while posterior foramina relatively short. Posterior margin of mastoid chamber extends to level of occipital condyle but never exceeds supraoccipital bone. Posterior superior margin of mastoid chamber more inflated than inferior margin (
<figureCitation box="[961,1075,689,714]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1275,1297]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,303,1253]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[264,1323,303,1253]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 36. A. Dorsal,B. Ventral, C. Lateral views of the skull, and D. Upper maxillary teeth for Gerbillus andersoni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202849/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figure 36</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1055,1593,1615]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202847/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" startId="33.[151,250,1593,1615]" targetBox="[151,1436,766,1571]" targetPageId="33">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1055,1593,1615]" box="[151,1055,1593,1615]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,1593,1615]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">FIGURE 35.</emphasis>
Anderson’s gerbil, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Winton" authorityYear="1902" box="[487,690,1593,1615]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis box="[487,690,1593,1615]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Gerbillus andersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(photo by Mohammad Abu Baker).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1654,2003]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,538,1654,1679]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Localities: Previous records.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="= El Quweira (Allen, 1915)" authorityName="El Quweira (Allen" authorityYear="1915" box="[546,997,1654,1679]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gerbillus">
<emphasis box="[546,677,1654,1679]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. gerbillus</emphasis>
= El Quweira (
<bibRefCitation box="[851,989,1654,1679]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref30777" refString="Allen, G. M. (1915) Mammals obtained by the Phillips Palestine Expedition. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoolology of Harvard University, 59 (1), 3 - 14." type="journal article">Allen, 1915</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<quantity box="[1009,1081,1654,1679]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="km" value="22.0">22 km</quantity>
N El Quweira, 5 Km S Ra’s an Naqb (
<bibRefCitation box="[226,518,1690,1715]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref31502" refString="Atallah, S. I. &amp; Harrison, D. L. (1967) New records of rodents, bats and insectivores from the Arabian Peninsula. Journal of Zoology, London, 153 (3), 311 - 319. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1967. tb 04065. x" type="journal article">Atallah &amp; Harrison, 1967</bibRefCitation>
); S Ra’s an Naqb (Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2004) (
<figureCitation box="[1030,1137,1690,1715]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1927,1949]" captionTargetBox="[275,1307,732,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[264,1323,697,1905]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 37. Distribution of Anderson’s gerbil, Gerbillus andersoni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202851/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figure37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1654,2003]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1726,1751]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Habitat:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Winton" authorityYear="1902" box="[309,455,1726,1751]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis box="[309,455,1726,1751]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. andersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in areas of light sand dunes dominated with 
<emphasis box="[1085,1307,1726,1751]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Anabasis 
<taxonomicName box="[1197,1307,1726,1751]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Acomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="articulata">articulata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. It lives in association with the hairy-footed gerbil, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" box="[621,773,1762,1787]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis box="[621,773,1762,1787]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the fat sand rat, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cretzschmar" authorityYear="1828" box="[1028,1254,1762,1787]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Psammomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obesus">
<emphasis box="[1028,1254,1762,1787]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Psammomys obesus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Burrows of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Winton" authorityYear="1902" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. andersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could not be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" box="[737,887,1798,1823]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cheesmani">
<emphasis box="[737,887,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">G. cheesmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Anderson's gerbil is a strictly nocturnal species (
<bibRefCitation box="[158,455,1834,1859]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref30180" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 a) A morphometric and taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbillus in Jordan with notes on its current distribution. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 53, 177 - 204." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1654,2003]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,1870,1895]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Biology</emphasis>
: Anderson’s gerbil is a nocturnal animal, specialized on seeds (i.e. 
<emphasis box="[1045,1238,1870,1895]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Thymelea 
<taxonomicName box="[1161,1238,1870,1895]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Herniaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirsute">hirsute</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
). It breeds in late winter or early spring, coinciding with the annual seed shedding. Female gives birth to a litter of three to seven offspring after a gestation period that lasts for 20 to 22 days.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1654,2003]" lastBlockId="34.[151,1437,151,248]" lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1978,2003]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks</emphasis>
: The distribution of this species is known only from the sand desert south of Ra’s an Naqb. Its presense in 
<collectingCountry box="[289,364,151,176]" name="Jordan" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Jordan</collectingCountry>
may represent a relict population. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Winton" authorityYear="1902" box="[772,918,151,176]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andersoni">
<emphasis box="[772,918,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">G. andersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have 2N=40 and FN = 80 (male specimen). There are 14 metacentric and 24 submetacentric autosomes. The X and Y chromosomes are medium and smallsized submetacentric, respectively (
<bibRefCitation box="[549,810,223,248]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" refId="ref30364" refString="Abu Baker, M., Khalil, A., Sheyab, F. &amp; Amr, Z. (2009) A karyotypic study on rodents of the genus Gerbillus collected from Jordan. Vertebrate Zoology, 59 (1), 111 - 116." type="journal article">
Abu Baker 
<emphasis box="[679,729,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">et al</emphasis>
., 2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
